Build Instructions
1. Mechanical Assembly

Bolt the 12Nm NEMA 34 stepper motor to the 3D printed housing using M5
Mount the base to your desk or rig using any type of clamps or just rest it on the table.
Slide the 3D printed quick release collar onto the motor shaft.
Tighten the M3 bolts on the collar to securely clamp it to the shaft.
Attach the YOUR steering wheel with the quick release system from (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5100966/files) on Thingiverse.
Wrap electrical tape around the wheel rim for better grip and feel if you decided to 3D print it.

2. Electronics Mounting

Stack the STM32F407 board directly on top of the Elecrow TMC4671 driver board.
Mount the stacked driver assembly to the base using M3 standoffs and screws that came with the OpenFFBoard.
Attach the 80mm cooling fan directly to the 3d printed housing using any bolts of choice.

3. Wiring

Connect the 48-60V power supply to the TMC4671 driver (VMOT = +, GND = -). Add a 10A fuse on the positive wire.
Connect the 10Ω 50W brake resistor across the PB+ and PB- terminals.
Wire the motor phases:
A+ and A- → Phase A terminals
B+ and B- → Phase B terminals

Wire the encoder to the ENC header on the TMC4671:
Encoder A+, B+, Z+, 5V, GND

Connect +5V and GND from the TMC4671 driver to the STM32F407 board.
Connect USB from the STM32F407 board to your PC.

IMPORTANT: Reference the KiCAD schematic I made and check it for yourself since it is possible I made a mistake

4. First Power-Up & Setup

Plug in the USB cable to the PC first (powers the STM32).
Turn on the 48-60V power supply.
Flash the latest OpenFFBoard firmware to the STM32F407.
Open the OpenFFBoard configurator and set:
Motor type: 2-phase stepper
Pole pairs: 50
Encoder: 1000 PPR (4000 CPR)

Start with very low torque (20-30%) and gradually tune the PID and filters.

Safety Note:
This wheel can produce strong torque. Always start with low torque settings and test carefully. Do not put your hands near the wheel during initial testing. I am not liable for any injuries or faliures that will result in and damages. Everything is done at your own risk.
